item.title: Finally!
item.description: Yall, this has been the most trying 2 years of my life. Had to have a double sided ankle surgery due to a car accident, get part of my cervix cut off to avoid cancer, got laid off work, went through a divorce, struggle with my child through her own medical issues, be turned down over and over and over again for work, it has been emotionally and physically brutal. The only thing that got me through was the settlement check from my car accident. I emptied my retirement accounts, had to sell my car and buy a beater. Use food pantries and get on SNAP. This month you guys rescued Christmas and raised enough money for me to make one last mortgage payment for January. My ship was sinking fast. I finally got a job. And I could not be more grateful! I'm a bookkeeper by trade for the last decade. I landed a job as a security officer for a hospital of all things. The hours are rough 9 pm to 6 am and I know I'm going to be dealing with people having some very bad days and im going to be absolutely exhausted. But I have never been more grateful to be employed. Idk how long I will be at this place, and ill still be looking for opportunities that arise but I wont be writing 5 cover letters a day and making uncountable micro adjustments to my resume everyday. I'm going to lose my health coverage because ill be making about $300 a month too much to qualify for Medicaid anymore but I'll be able to pay my bills and not loose my home and not feel like im slowly being crushed everyday in worthlessness. All that to say, this is unbelievably relieving.

item.title: Things seen this week during structural assessments!
item.description:
As we wrap up another year of structural assessments across Los Angeles and Orange County, we wanted to take a moment to highlight some of our most jaw-dropping, bizarre and downright fascinating things we’ve encountered on our site visits. These photos offer a behind-the-scenes look at the challenges that often go unseen. We’ve gathered some of the most memorable moments from 2025 to share with you. Starting off with this sunroom overlooking the hillside that seems like a nice spot to work out.
However, this is what’s supporting it: unpermitted construction with wood framing that is directly in contact with soil. This poses a major issue as it can lead to rapid wood rot and attract termites.
Our team immediately began working with the Vice Mayor of Pasadena to handle anything on his radar with the resources we have, regardless of the scope. His primary concern was exit roads for evacuation, so we cleared roads, be it removing a massive 100-year-old downed cypress tree blocking 3,000 homes, or just clearing and hauling branches and brush.
The destruction and loss are hard to believe, and seeing our community lose everything has been hard to accept. Shoutout to our team who always responds, no matter what or when. We were providing trucks and crews to help property owners move salvageable belongings, cut hazardous trees, create property access, and more.
Called out by the HOA president after the Pacific Palisades fires, our team assessed a neighborhood where several homes were lost and large portions of the hillside were left scorched, with remaining vegetation no longer able to provide natural soil stability; to help reduce the risk of erosion and mud movement ahead of incoming rain, we installed protective tarping across vulnerable areas to stabilize the slope and help protect the surrounding homes, providing an added layer of support while the community begins the recovery process.
Water runoff from above the hillside caused a partial slope failure. Because of this, the city storm drain shifted, which caused a breach and more water seepage, ultimately leading to this retaining wall failing. For now, the spiral staircase is pretty much the only thing keeping the wall from collapsing.
This Palisades home survived the wildfire, but just days later, a mudslide destroyed the property, splitting it in half. After a fire, the risk of slope failure increases significantly. With vegetation gone, the soil loses its natural stability, making it more prone to sliding.
The support columns in this commercial building have sustained damage from forklifts crashing into them.
This unreinforced wall made up of recycled concrete also failed during heavy rainfall. In this case it was also due to hydrostatic pressure, which occurs when water builds up behind a wall and exerts pressure against it.
This was found beneath a home addition, where cinder blocks were used instead of proper piers. This is not how a post-and-pier system is meant to be built and does not provide adequate structural support.
This post-and-pier system has no structural integrity, no proper support, and definitely no excuse for a Mickey Mouse repair like this. Jenga anyone?
A car lost control and crashed directly into the structural post of this building, causing serious damage.
A drunk driver went airborne and collided into this pedestrian bridge. The crash completely cut off access between two sides of the neighborhood. The bridge was left unusable and what was once a direct route now required a long detour
We were brought in under an emergency declaration to engineer, design, and get full approval through the City of Stanton and Orange County to get this bridge rebuilt and reopened as quickly as possible. Check out our video for a full walkthrough of the project, including behind-the-scenes photos, progress clips, and more context on what went into the rebuild. https://youtu.be/85kcmuH8diQ?si=I6ZCXm2J1tMgZzER
Years of deferred maintenance, wood rot, and termite damage have taken their toll on this staircase. It’s a clear example of what can happen when basic upkeep is ignored.
This retaining wall is showing serious signs of structural failure. This type of crack can be caused by poor drainage and soil movement. When drainage is inadequate, water accumulates in the soil, increasing lateral pressure on the wall structure. Over time, this pressure can lead to significant cracking, displacement, or even collapse if not addressed promptly. Hey Siri play Under Pressure by Queen.
Cute landscaping… until the hillside files for eviction. River-rock retaining walls are non-conforming, not engineered, and they never have the drainage needed to resist soil pressure. Dirt and rocks aren’t a retaining wall—proper reinforcement and drainage are.
This hillside tried to relocate itself into the backyard. Soil movement caused the fencing and retaining elements to collapse. Without proper retaining systems and drainage, erosion will continue and the slope will keep shifting downhill.
Thanks for being part of our community and for checking in with us week after week. We share these posts to help bring awareness to what’s happening behind walls, under slabs, and on hillsides that most people never get to see. If your home or property ever needs a structural assessment or if something doesn’t feel right, reach out to us at Alpha Structural. We’ll see you again next week at 2 PM. Appreciate you all.

item.title: Here's a thing or two to make you chuckle sensibly or quirk a smile
item.description: So this one is a special one in my Discord DM's. I love languages, I love puns, and I love self-made portmonteaus, but this was just a happy little accident I saw when visiting the library in Halmstad. Essentially, it's the embodiment of Swenglish. Us Swedes are decently good at English, but sometimes a bit of our native language intermingles with the foreign words inside our brains. The way I read it, the English translation says the door is a bit anxious, or perhaps frightened, rather than it is about to raise an alarm if trespassed upon. Or mayhap it is correct to say that a door is alarmed in that context? Either way, this phrasing amused me and I had to send it to my favourite New Yorker. And now, you've all seen it too! The door is alarmed
